00:00:22.060 --> 00:00:24.896
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
So today, we'll

00:00:24.896 --> 00:00:26.020
talk about cost estimation.

00:00:26.020 --> 00:00:30.930
It's the first of the
modeling lectures.

00:00:30.930 --> 00:00:33.460
We'll talk very briefly
about the role--

00:00:33.460 --> 00:00:36.180
the different roles
that cost models

00:00:36.180 --> 00:00:39.090
have in transit agencies.

00:00:39.090 --> 00:00:41.800
And then we'll discuss
three types of--

00:00:41.800 --> 00:00:43.990
three categories of cost models.

00:00:43.990 --> 00:00:45.350
So all right, let's get into it.

00:00:45.350 --> 00:00:48.840
So what are the roles?

00:00:48.840 --> 00:00:50.760
How could cost models be used?

00:00:50.760 --> 00:00:55.680
And to start, a cost model is
a model, a mathematical model

00:00:55.680 --> 00:00:58.680
that takes some
variables and predicts

00:00:58.680 --> 00:00:59.865
some costs for the agency.

00:00:59.865 --> 00:01:01.190
It could be operational cost.

00:01:01.190 --> 00:01:02.700
It could be fixed cost.

00:01:02.700 --> 00:01:04.379
So how could these be used?

00:01:04.379 --> 00:01:07.590
The first row is predicting
the cost change associated

00:01:07.590 --> 00:01:08.970
with a service change.

00:01:08.970 --> 00:01:13.170
So this is a very
traditional typical example.

00:01:13.170 --> 00:01:15.400
So you might extend
the route as we

00:01:15.400 --> 00:01:19.110
are thinking about in this
assignment, Route 1770A,

00:01:19.110 --> 00:01:20.100
extending it.

00:01:20.100 --> 00:01:24.180
And you might wonder, how much
will that cost to operate?

00:01:24.180 --> 00:01:26.670
So you could use a cost
model in that situation.

00:01:26.670 --> 00:01:28.890
Or maybe there's a wider
increase in service.

00:01:28.890 --> 00:01:32.640
Maybe service is being
expanded from ending

00:01:32.640 --> 00:01:34.980
at 2 AM to running 24 hours.

00:01:34.980 --> 00:01:36.930
How much would that cost?

00:01:36.930 --> 00:01:39.840
So these are the kinds of
questions, service changes

00:01:39.840 --> 00:01:42.450
that you might want to
have an idea of how much

00:01:42.450 --> 00:01:45.150
will it cost me.

00:01:45.150 --> 00:01:50.530
So they are often concerned with
marginal or incremental costs,

00:01:50.530 --> 00:01:52.450
especially in this application.

00:01:52.450 --> 00:02:00.220
So if you expand service to
cover all night, for example,

00:02:00.220 --> 00:02:03.000
you may not need that--
that change may not

00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:06.060
trigger the need for
a new bus maintenance

00:02:06.060 --> 00:02:09.660
facility, or some large
capital expenditure.

00:02:09.660 --> 00:02:12.510
So we're talking here about
per-- incremental cost.

00:02:12.510 --> 00:02:14.760
As I add buses, or
as I add bus hours,

00:02:14.760 --> 00:02:19.490
or as I add driver hours,
how much extra do I pay?

00:02:19.490 --> 00:02:22.270
You have different results
over different time periods.

00:02:22.270 --> 00:02:23.590
This is important.

00:02:23.590 --> 00:02:27.060
It doesn't cost the same to run
service off-peak or at night

00:02:27.060 --> 00:02:28.725
as it does on-peak.

00:02:28.725 --> 00:02:31.640
I will talk more about
that later in this lecture.

00:02:31.640 --> 00:02:34.030
But having that in mind,
and having a cost model that

00:02:34.030 --> 00:02:36.240
is sensitive to
time periods might

00:02:36.240 --> 00:02:40.880
be very important to
get accurate estimates.

00:02:40.880 --> 00:02:43.080
OK, so these models
can also be used

00:02:43.080 --> 00:02:45.720
for routine performance
monitoring and service policy

00:02:45.720 --> 00:02:46.350
triggers.

00:02:46.350 --> 00:02:49.350
You might remember from
the short-term planning

00:02:49.350 --> 00:02:53.850
lectures that there are some
processes where every bus

00:02:53.850 --> 00:02:54.960
route might be reviewed.

00:02:54.960 --> 00:02:58.530
And you might decide that
you need to add service

00:02:58.530 --> 00:03:00.000
based on its performance.

00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:03.570
Or you might decide
that a bus route

00:03:03.570 --> 00:03:08.710
isn't meeting the requirements
to be financially sustainable.

00:03:08.710 --> 00:03:11.130
So if you are considering
removing, dropping

00:03:11.130 --> 00:03:14.670
service [INAUDIBLE],, how much
will you save by doing that?

00:03:14.670 --> 00:03:17.770
All of those are
applications of bus mode.

00:03:17.770 --> 00:03:19.590
OK, the second point
here is that you

00:03:19.590 --> 00:03:21.480
can predict the cost
change associated

00:03:21.480 --> 00:03:24.090
with the change in a
production process.

00:03:24.090 --> 00:03:26.260
Now, we're not talking
so much about service,

00:03:26.260 --> 00:03:28.260
but we're thinking
of, what happens

00:03:28.260 --> 00:03:33.210
if I'm in a labor agreement
that does not allow part timers,

00:03:33.210 --> 00:03:37.200
and now has negotiated the
ability to hire part timers?

00:03:37.200 --> 00:03:40.900
What will that do to cost,
sort of cost structure?

00:03:40.900 --> 00:03:43.290
What about if I want to
contract out maintenance work?

00:03:43.290 --> 00:03:45.180
I'm doing that
right now in-house.

00:03:45.180 --> 00:03:48.980
And now maybe for a
portion or for all of it,

00:03:48.980 --> 00:03:52.800
we are looking at
public-private partnerships

00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:55.320
to contract out
maintenance work.

00:03:55.320 --> 00:03:57.630
Or contracting out suburban
bus routes-- for instance,

00:03:57.630 --> 00:03:59.400
I have low ridership.

00:03:59.400 --> 00:04:01.170
And they're kind of
on the outskirts.

00:04:01.170 --> 00:04:03.180
You don't want to drop
service, but maybe you

00:04:03.180 --> 00:04:05.610
don't need big 40-foot
buses and you can run them

00:04:05.610 --> 00:04:07.590
with smaller buses.

00:04:07.590 --> 00:04:09.270
Could you contract those out?

00:04:09.270 --> 00:04:11.070
What will that do to cost?

00:04:11.070 --> 00:04:13.565
New fare technology, the MBTA--

00:04:13.565 --> 00:04:15.690
I don't know who was
here a long time ago.

00:04:15.690 --> 00:04:16.875
We had tokens here.

00:04:16.875 --> 00:04:18.570
And we moved to the CharlieCard.

00:04:18.570 --> 00:04:21.930
And now the MBTA is thinking
about the next generation

00:04:21.930 --> 00:04:26.340
of fare collection for Boston.

00:04:26.340 --> 00:04:28.680
AUDIENCE: When was the
CharlieCard invented?

00:04:28.680 --> 00:04:29.535
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
I don't remember the year.

00:04:29.535 --> 00:04:29.700
AUDIENCE: 2005.

00:04:29.700 --> 00:04:30.600
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
But it was--

00:04:30.600 --> 00:04:31.766
yeah, it was the mid-2000s--

00:04:31.766 --> 00:04:33.000
AUDIENCE: 2005.

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:35.630
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
--because I remember in 2004

00:04:35.630 --> 00:04:37.864
there being tokens still.

00:04:37.864 --> 00:04:39.780
AUDIENCE: I think the
last station with tokens

00:04:39.780 --> 00:04:42.844
was Government Center in 2006.

00:04:42.844 --> 00:04:44.760
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
So anytime something

00:04:44.760 --> 00:04:47.790
like this happens,
there is a change

00:04:47.790 --> 00:04:49.890
in costs, administration costs.

00:04:49.890 --> 00:04:54.300
And the recovery of the fare
recovery ratio might change.

00:04:54.300 --> 00:04:56.435
So can we model that?

00:04:56.435 --> 00:04:59.130
And can we use cost models
to predict those changes

00:04:59.130 --> 00:05:02.110
in cost or in revenue?

00:05:02.110 --> 00:05:06.420
OK, then another sort of third
and very important application,

00:05:06.420 --> 00:05:10.530
not so much in Boston
right now, but certainly

00:05:10.530 --> 00:05:13.800
in other jurisdictions,
is the allocation

00:05:13.800 --> 00:05:16.540
of subsidy required
by jurisdiction.

00:05:16.540 --> 00:05:20.152
So if you look at, for example,
the WMATA in Washington, DC,

00:05:20.152 --> 00:05:21.402
there are different districts.

00:05:21.402 --> 00:05:23.590
And they all have
to pay for service.

00:05:23.590 --> 00:05:30.460
So there are many examples of
this over the states and also

00:05:30.460 --> 00:05:36.250
internationally, where different
jurisdictions are essentially

00:05:36.250 --> 00:05:40.840
partnering to subsidize
public transportation service.

00:05:40.840 --> 00:05:46.580
And we know what the total
cost of operation is.

00:05:46.580 --> 00:05:50.180
So how much is fair that
each restriction pay?

00:05:50.180 --> 00:05:52.804
According to size, according
to how many people--

00:05:52.804 --> 00:05:54.470
often, it's according
to how many people

00:05:54.470 --> 00:05:58.720
ride from those jurisdictions.

00:05:58.720 --> 00:06:03.020
So you might have a data
collection to figure out

00:06:03.020 --> 00:06:06.780
how many people are taking buses
from each of the jurisdictions.

00:06:06.780 --> 00:06:09.770
And then you need to allocate
a cost allocation model

00:06:09.770 --> 00:06:12.920
to take all of the costs,
including the things that

00:06:12.920 --> 00:06:18.020
are sort of more obvious, like
the bus hours that operate

00:06:18.020 --> 00:06:20.750
in those jurisdictions, but also
things that are not directly

00:06:20.750 --> 00:06:23.480
connected to the jurisdictions,
such as administration

00:06:23.480 --> 00:06:26.180
costs, and facility
maintenance, and those things.

00:06:26.180 --> 00:06:28.920
So all of that needs to be
allocated to each jurisdiction

00:06:28.920 --> 00:06:33.230
so that the cost can be
evenly or fairly split.

00:06:33.230 --> 00:06:36.620
And doing that right
is critical, often,

00:06:36.620 --> 00:06:39.770
even for the decision
to participate or not

00:06:39.770 --> 00:06:42.800
in this program.

00:06:42.800 --> 00:06:43.670
Question?

00:06:43.670 --> 00:06:45.370
AUDIENCE: For jurisdictions,
you mentioned Washington.

00:06:45.370 --> 00:06:47.330
Would that be like
Virginia and Washington DC?

00:06:47.330 --> 00:06:47.870
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Yeah.

00:06:47.870 --> 00:06:49.760
AUDIENCE: Or in New York,
it would be New York--

00:06:49.760 --> 00:06:51.230
Port Authority of New
York and New Jersey?

00:06:51.230 --> 00:06:51.428
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Yeah.

00:06:51.428 --> 00:06:53.870
AUDIENCE: Or would you
also mean, like, counties?

00:06:53.870 --> 00:06:55.911
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
There are many examples

00:06:55.911 --> 00:07:00.470
and different structures of how
different jurisdictions come

00:07:00.470 --> 00:07:02.070
together to provide service.

00:07:02.070 --> 00:07:05.800
So in some cases, you have
many different operators,

00:07:05.800 --> 00:07:08.630
and more commonly in
the West of the US,

00:07:08.630 --> 00:07:13.490
many different operators all
providing service somehow.

00:07:13.490 --> 00:07:16.490
In other cases, you have
one major operator funded

00:07:16.490 --> 00:07:20.720
by different jurisdictions.

00:07:20.720 --> 00:07:23.280
All right, so you
might remember,

00:07:23.280 --> 00:07:26.120
we've only talked about
modal capacities and costs

00:07:26.120 --> 00:07:31.070
that, especially in the
US, in North America,

00:07:31.070 --> 00:07:35.300
costs are divided into capital
expenditures and operations

00:07:35.300 --> 00:07:36.350
expenditures.

00:07:36.350 --> 00:07:39.120
So capital costs have to do
with the purchase of vehicles,

00:07:39.120 --> 00:07:45.600
or the [INAUDIBLE] of
vehicles, heavy maintenance,

00:07:45.600 --> 00:07:48.950
the fixed facility
construction, so construction

00:07:48.950 --> 00:07:54.010
or major repairs of
trucks, garage, stations,

00:07:54.010 --> 00:07:56.600
bus stops, things
like that, and then

00:07:56.600 --> 00:08:00.470
other long-term physical assets,
so administration buildings,

00:08:00.470 --> 00:08:02.310
and things like that.

00:08:02.310 --> 00:08:04.020
And then there's
operating costs.

00:08:04.020 --> 00:08:05.310
So those have to do with--

00:08:05.310 --> 00:08:07.160
they're more
proportional to how much

00:08:07.160 --> 00:08:11.630
service you output, so labor
wages and benefits, materials

00:08:11.630 --> 00:08:12.570
and supplies.

00:08:12.570 --> 00:08:17.440
Materials includes fuel,
and tires, and electricity

00:08:17.440 --> 00:08:20.480
to run the-- power the metro.

00:08:20.480 --> 00:08:23.780
Then there's agency
administration and other kinds

00:08:23.780 --> 00:08:25.370
of expenses of this nature.

00:08:25.370 --> 00:08:29.910
So it's important to
keep those two in mind,

00:08:29.910 --> 00:08:36.150
because the cost
models that we specify

00:08:36.150 --> 00:08:38.220
should take this
into consideration

00:08:38.220 --> 00:08:43.500
and be able to allocate
the capital and operating

00:08:43.500 --> 00:08:45.590
expenses separately.

00:08:45.590 --> 00:08:48.350
All right, so there are
three types of cost models

00:08:48.350 --> 00:08:49.750
that we're going to discuss.

00:08:49.750 --> 00:08:52.230
The first is a fully
allocated causal factor model.

00:08:52.230 --> 00:08:54.770
It's the simplest of
ones that we'll discuss.

00:08:54.770 --> 00:08:56.450
One of the problems
with that model

00:08:56.450 --> 00:09:01.100
is that it allocates all of
the costs to some categories.

00:09:01.100 --> 00:09:04.450
And it's not sensitive
to time periods.

00:09:04.450 --> 00:09:08.730
As I said earlier, some costs
vary a lot by time period.

00:09:08.730 --> 00:09:12.620
So the second model essentially
is a variation or an extension

00:09:12.620 --> 00:09:16.940
of the first one, where we do
take some specific costs that

00:09:16.940 --> 00:09:20.240
are very sensitive to
time and capture that,

00:09:20.240 --> 00:09:22.160
those differences, over time.

00:09:22.160 --> 00:09:24.980
And then we'll talk about
incremental fixed/variable cost

00:09:24.980 --> 00:09:25.480
models.

00:09:25.480 --> 00:09:29.440
We're going to give examples
of all of these using MBTA bus

00:09:29.440 --> 00:09:31.350
from the '90s as an example.

00:09:31.350 --> 00:09:33.770
Let's start with the first
one, the fully allocated

00:09:33.770 --> 00:09:34.650
causal factor model.

00:09:34.650 --> 00:09:36.860
So here's what you do.

00:09:36.860 --> 00:09:38.870
You select some causal factors.

00:09:38.870 --> 00:09:43.430
So these are not necessarily--
maybe causal factor is one

00:09:43.430 --> 00:09:47.280
of the best term, but
that's what this model is--

00:09:47.280 --> 00:09:48.290
class is called.

00:09:48.290 --> 00:09:50.750
I would say, these are
explanatory variables more

00:09:50.750 --> 00:09:51.600
than causal factors.

00:09:51.600 --> 00:09:54.930
They don't have to
cause the cost directly,

00:09:54.930 --> 00:09:59.000
but they are used as explanatory
variables in a model of cost.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:03.240
So then you assign each expense
type to each of the factors.

00:10:03.240 --> 00:10:06.410
So for example, operator
wages and benefits,

00:10:06.410 --> 00:10:07.310
where would that go?

00:10:07.310 --> 00:10:12.260
If you were thinking of three
kinds of explanatory variables,

00:10:12.260 --> 00:10:15.234
vehicle hours being one,
vehicle miles being the second,

00:10:15.234 --> 00:10:16.650
and peak vehicles
being the third,

00:10:16.650 --> 00:10:19.610
and you're going to assign
every cost you incur

00:10:19.610 --> 00:10:24.050
to one of those three, then
operator wages and benefits

00:10:24.050 --> 00:10:27.800
are more appropriately
assigned to vehicle hours,

00:10:27.800 --> 00:10:30.950
because the pay
drivers by the hour,

00:10:30.950 --> 00:10:35.380
so this is the one that it
relates to most closely.

00:10:35.380 --> 00:10:38.780
Fuel-- so fuel may be a
combination of vehicle hours

00:10:38.780 --> 00:10:39.560
and vehicle miles.

00:10:39.560 --> 00:10:43.250
Or if you have to assign them
to one, then vehicle miles--

00:10:43.250 --> 00:10:46.940
you think of the fuel
mileage of vehicles.

00:10:46.940 --> 00:10:50.930
So that's the one
that most closely

00:10:50.930 --> 00:10:55.700
relates vehicle miles to fuel.

00:10:55.700 --> 00:10:59.092
And then administration--
well, administration, you

00:10:59.092 --> 00:11:00.800
might want to assign
it to peak vehicles,

00:11:00.800 --> 00:11:03.376
because peak vehicles is a proxy
for how big is this agency.

00:11:03.376 --> 00:11:05.750
And the bigger that agency,
the bigger the administration

00:11:05.750 --> 00:11:06.380
costs.

00:11:06.380 --> 00:11:09.980
So it's one way of
assigning these things.

00:11:09.980 --> 00:11:13.232
So this is an example.

00:11:13.232 --> 00:11:14.690
After you do all
those assignments,

00:11:14.690 --> 00:11:18.720
you calculate the average
costs for each of the factors.

00:11:18.720 --> 00:11:23.192
So you have, for
example, the cost

00:11:23.192 --> 00:11:25.400
assigned to vehicle hours
divided by the total number

00:11:25.400 --> 00:11:26.480
of vehicle hours.

00:11:26.480 --> 00:11:28.460
And you have those unit costs.

00:11:28.460 --> 00:11:30.530
And then the cost
model is simply

00:11:30.530 --> 00:11:32.350
each of those unit
costs divided--

00:11:32.350 --> 00:11:35.000
or multiplied by the three
explanatory variables

00:11:35.000 --> 00:11:36.290
that you included.

00:11:36.290 --> 00:11:39.260
So you multiply your
unit vehicle hour cost

00:11:39.260 --> 00:11:42.350
by the number of vehicle
hours, your unit vehicle miles

00:11:42.350 --> 00:11:45.020
cost by vehicle miles,
and your unit peak

00:11:45.020 --> 00:11:47.070
vehicles cost by peak vehicles.

00:11:47.070 --> 00:11:50.040
And that is the total
cost of the agency.

00:11:50.040 --> 00:11:50.540
Questions?

00:11:50.540 --> 00:11:52.290
AUDIENCE: This assumes
that you're somehow

00:11:52.290 --> 00:11:54.710
able to split the data
into those categories,

00:11:54.710 --> 00:11:57.440
to say the costs assigned
to vehicle hours are x.

00:11:57.440 --> 00:11:59.870
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Yes, so that's one

00:11:59.870 --> 00:12:03.080
of the characteristics and
perhaps weaknesses of this kind

00:12:03.080 --> 00:12:05.540
of model, that it requires
the judgment of the person

00:12:05.540 --> 00:12:06.590
to assign--

00:12:06.590 --> 00:12:08.747
to first, to generate
these classes

00:12:08.747 --> 00:12:10.580
and these explanatory
variables, and second,

00:12:10.580 --> 00:12:14.690
to assign them to each
cost of this class or each

00:12:14.690 --> 00:12:20.090
account in a ledger to each of
these explanatory variables.

00:12:20.090 --> 00:12:25.680
So But these models are
used in the industry.

00:12:25.680 --> 00:12:30.151
So if you plug in the
number of vehicle hours,

00:12:30.151 --> 00:12:31.650
and vehicle miles,
and peak vehicles

00:12:31.650 --> 00:12:33.700
that you used to
estimate this model,

00:12:33.700 --> 00:12:37.860
then you're just going
to get the total cost

00:12:37.860 --> 00:12:39.460
of operations or of--

00:12:39.460 --> 00:12:45.330
or total combined cost
on the same period

00:12:45.330 --> 00:12:47.400
that this data came from.

00:12:47.400 --> 00:12:51.630
But more interestingly,
if you are considering

00:12:51.630 --> 00:12:55.080
expanding service, and that will
increase vehicle hours, vehicle

00:12:55.080 --> 00:12:57.390
miles, and peak
vehicles, then this model

00:12:57.390 --> 00:13:00.960
will work in some
ways to forecast

00:13:00.960 --> 00:13:05.250
what the total cost will be
after you grow your agency.

00:13:05.250 --> 00:13:08.032
So this is one application
of this simple model.

00:13:08.032 --> 00:13:10.490
AUDIENCE: Is there a time unit
that you're supposed to use,

00:13:10.490 --> 00:13:12.240
like a full year to
capture [INAUDIBLE]??

00:13:12.240 --> 00:13:14.031
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
This is up to you

00:13:14.031 --> 00:13:15.756
as well, another judgment call.

00:13:15.756 --> 00:13:17.640
It shouldn't be one day, but--

00:13:17.640 --> 00:13:21.340
because you want to see
all the kinds of expenses.

00:13:21.340 --> 00:13:25.670
So I think a year makes
sense, a fiscal year,

00:13:25.670 --> 00:13:30.870
because you will have to put
out a statement for [INAUDIBLE]..

00:13:30.870 --> 00:13:34.040
You do accounting on
that fiscal year basis.

00:13:34.040 --> 00:13:41.190
OK, so here's an example from
1996 of a bus on the MBTA.

00:13:41.190 --> 00:13:44.130
So we have those three
variables that we

00:13:44.130 --> 00:13:45.780
talked about--
vehicle hours, vehicle

00:13:45.780 --> 00:13:47.820
miles, and peak vehicles.

00:13:47.820 --> 00:13:51.650
We divide each of those
into variable or fixed.

00:13:51.650 --> 00:13:54.870
So some of the expenses
are considered variable,

00:13:54.870 --> 00:13:59.070
because they sort of scale up
more linearly as you increase

00:13:59.070 --> 00:14:00.420
the number of vehicle hours.

00:14:00.420 --> 00:14:03.240
And others are more
fixed expenses.

00:14:03.240 --> 00:14:08.100
You wouldn't expect to
get extra fixed costs

00:14:08.100 --> 00:14:10.020
by adding a few buses, right?

00:14:10.020 --> 00:14:13.410
So one example of
that is, if you

00:14:13.410 --> 00:14:17.370
get 10 more buses
for a new bus route,

00:14:17.370 --> 00:14:19.440
you don't need a new
maintenance facility.

00:14:19.440 --> 00:14:21.030
So your maintenance
facility might

00:14:21.030 --> 00:14:22.980
be considered a fixed expense.

00:14:22.980 --> 00:14:24.840
And you might want a
variable cost model

00:14:24.840 --> 00:14:28.200
to predict the changes
of that small change

00:14:28.200 --> 00:14:29.740
or that marginal change.

00:14:29.740 --> 00:14:33.520
So that's why we divide things
into fixed and variable.

00:14:33.520 --> 00:14:39.120
The total cost to be
allocated is $173.6 million.

00:14:39.120 --> 00:14:43.720
And we divide it over these
six categories, so the three

00:14:43.720 --> 00:14:49.630
variables and their fixed
and variable variance.

00:14:49.630 --> 00:14:54.160
Here we have the percentages
of each and the unit costs.

00:14:57.220 --> 00:15:01.370
So now, what are possible cost
models following this approach?

00:15:01.370 --> 00:15:05.140
A first and simple one,
a very traditional model,

00:15:05.140 --> 00:15:06.490
is the first one listed here.

00:15:06.490 --> 00:15:13.120
So 39.82, which is the total
unit cost of revenue vehicle

00:15:13.120 --> 00:15:16.660
hours-- it's the sum
of 37.13 and 2.69--

00:15:16.660 --> 00:15:19.780
times the number of revenue
vehicle hours, and then 2.41,

00:15:19.780 --> 00:15:25.410
which is the sum of 2.270 and
0.14 times revenue vehicle

00:15:25.410 --> 00:15:27.750
miles times some factor.

00:15:27.750 --> 00:15:31.440
And that factor,
essentially here, we have--

00:15:33.984 --> 00:15:35.400
we're not capturing
the difference

00:15:35.400 --> 00:15:37.320
between fixed and
variable costs.

00:15:37.320 --> 00:15:41.707
So that's why we add them
up here, 39.82 and 2.41.

00:15:41.707 --> 00:15:43.290
The other characteristic
of this model

00:15:43.290 --> 00:15:45.660
is that it does not
have peak vehicles

00:15:45.660 --> 00:15:47.430
as an explanatory variable.

00:15:47.430 --> 00:15:51.090
So we address that with
this adjustment factor.

00:15:51.090 --> 00:15:57.660
If you take the total
cost, which is 173.6,

00:15:57.660 --> 00:16:05.550
and you divide it by the sum
of the unit costs for revenue

00:16:05.550 --> 00:16:09.310
vehicle hours and revenue
vehicle miles, you get 1.26.

00:16:09.310 --> 00:16:11.550
And that's the
adjustment factor.

00:16:11.550 --> 00:16:16.112
So any questions--

00:16:16.112 --> 00:16:16.820
AUDIENCE: Sorry--

00:16:16.820 --> 00:16:18.778
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
--with that approach?

00:16:18.778 --> 00:16:21.470
AUDIENCE: You said the 1.26
is calculated by doing what?

00:16:21.470 --> 00:16:23.761
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Let me write it down for you.

00:16:25.680 --> 00:16:40.042
So you have a total of 173.6.

00:16:40.042 --> 00:16:41.130
And that's a total.

00:16:44.610 --> 00:16:49.830
And you divide it by the total
of the total number of unit

00:16:49.830 --> 00:16:53.110
costs that you are capturing
with explanatory variables,

00:16:53.110 --> 00:17:05.195
which is 29 plus 5.7 plus 50--

00:17:05.195 --> 00:17:06.140
AUDIENCE: Plus 3.

00:17:06.140 --> 00:17:07.598
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
--plus 3.

00:17:07.598 --> 00:17:08.800
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:17:08.800 --> 00:17:09.660
AUDIENCE: And last [INAUDIBLE]--

00:17:09.660 --> 00:17:10.860
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
--equals 1.261.

00:17:10.860 --> 00:17:12.079
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:17:17.624 --> 00:17:19.040
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
So we're

00:17:19.040 --> 00:17:21.740
dividing the total by the
amount that we did capture.

00:17:21.740 --> 00:17:25.550
And then that factors
out of the model.

00:17:25.550 --> 00:17:28.520
So this is a very simple
model of a full annual cost

00:17:28.520 --> 00:17:30.830
for the agency.

00:17:30.830 --> 00:17:32.730
Here we're looking
at the fiscal year.

00:17:32.730 --> 00:17:35.750
And it's sensitive
to two variables.

00:17:35.750 --> 00:17:38.090
It's not sensitive
to time period.

00:17:38.090 --> 00:17:41.990
And it's mixing fixed
and variable costs.

00:17:41.990 --> 00:17:46.054
So this model may not be the
best one for some applications.

00:17:46.054 --> 00:17:47.720
AUDIENCE: But just,
what's the intuition

00:17:47.720 --> 00:17:50.420
behind using vehicle
hours and vehicle miles?

00:17:50.420 --> 00:17:52.545
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
It's something that you--

00:17:52.545 --> 00:17:54.230
that agencies always
measure and report,

00:17:54.230 --> 00:17:58.490
so it's something that there's
already a data collection

00:17:58.490 --> 00:18:00.740
effort for it.

00:18:00.740 --> 00:18:03.830
If you think about especially
the traditional applications

00:18:03.830 --> 00:18:07.270
without automatic
data collection,

00:18:07.270 --> 00:18:10.220
there is an effort
to measure anything

00:18:10.220 --> 00:18:15.720
you deliver to collect how
much output you produce.

00:18:15.720 --> 00:18:18.090
And so we already have that.

00:18:18.090 --> 00:18:21.920
It's something that then you can
use as an explanatory variable.

00:18:21.920 --> 00:18:23.330
And it relates to service.

00:18:23.330 --> 00:18:25.650
So it's your service output.

00:18:28.920 --> 00:18:30.330
These are variables
that are also

00:18:30.330 --> 00:18:33.960
going to be found in any
service funding proposal

00:18:33.960 --> 00:18:36.150
in some way or another.

00:18:36.150 --> 00:18:39.574
If you extend routes, then
that increases both of these.

00:18:39.574 --> 00:18:41.490
AUDIENCE: I guess my
other question was, like,

00:18:41.490 --> 00:18:45.870
what's the intuition behind
vehicle hours being relatively

00:18:45.870 --> 00:18:47.400
more expensive
than vehicle miles?

00:18:47.400 --> 00:18:48.983
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
That depends

00:18:48.983 --> 00:18:52.672
on how you assign each of
these cost categories to it.

00:18:52.672 --> 00:18:55.005
AUDIENCE: It's not that, like,
operating a bus implies--

00:18:55.005 --> 00:18:57.213
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Well, I mean, in this case,

00:18:57.213 --> 00:18:57.780
wages are--

00:18:57.780 --> 00:19:01.520
wages and benefits are a
principle or one of the key--

00:19:01.520 --> 00:19:02.981
AUDIENCE: Got it, OK.

00:19:02.981 --> 00:19:04.980
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
--one of the key costs

00:19:04.980 --> 00:19:05.800
for the agency.

00:19:05.800 --> 00:19:09.030
And that's being reflected
entirely in vehicle hours.

00:19:09.030 --> 00:19:12.510
And potentially fuel
is a second one.

00:19:12.510 --> 00:19:15.660
And that is at least
partially covered

00:19:15.660 --> 00:19:17.890
by running vehicle hours.

00:19:17.890 --> 00:19:18.480
It could be.

00:19:18.480 --> 00:19:20.310
I'm not sure in
this model if it is.

00:19:20.310 --> 00:19:22.830
I suspect that everything was
assigned to vehicle miles,

00:19:22.830 --> 00:19:25.910
but it could be.

00:19:25.910 --> 00:19:30.410
So yeah, vehicle hours is
a proxy for more things.

00:19:30.410 --> 00:19:34.040
More costs are being
assigned to that variable.

00:19:34.040 --> 00:19:34.710
Eli?

00:19:34.710 --> 00:19:36.210
AUDIENCE: Can you
give some examples

00:19:36.210 --> 00:19:39.099
of variable and fixed costs?

00:19:39.099 --> 00:19:40.640
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Yeah, we'll

00:19:40.640 --> 00:19:43.060
actually see more of those
later in the lecture.

00:19:48.410 --> 00:19:54.190
Fuel is variable,
because as you drive more

00:19:54.190 --> 00:19:59.860
and you consume more--
and if you all of a sudden

00:19:59.860 --> 00:20:01.600
operate less
service, then you'll

00:20:01.600 --> 00:20:03.910
see that drop immediately.

00:20:03.910 --> 00:20:08.950
A fixed cost could be
the administration costs

00:20:08.950 --> 00:20:15.400
for, let's say, your
service planner team.

00:20:15.400 --> 00:20:17.140
So you've hired people.

00:20:17.140 --> 00:20:19.240
And if you drop
service a little bit,

00:20:19.240 --> 00:20:22.540
you're not necessarily
going to fire people.

00:20:22.540 --> 00:20:25.600
Or if you expand service,
you're not necessarily

00:20:25.600 --> 00:20:28.250
going to hire a bunch of people.

00:20:28.250 --> 00:20:30.040
Or you may not need
new offices for them.

00:20:30.040 --> 00:20:33.222
So all of those
things are more fixed.

00:20:33.222 --> 00:20:33.930
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:20:37.080 --> 00:20:39.330
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
OK, second model, so here we

00:20:39.330 --> 00:20:42.030
have the same first
part of the model,

00:20:42.030 --> 00:20:44.190
but now, instead of using
the adjustment factor,

00:20:44.190 --> 00:20:49.120
we directly take the unit cost
of peak vehicles and add it in.

00:20:49.120 --> 00:20:53.340
So now we have a model that
is sensitive to peak vehicles

00:20:53.340 --> 00:20:53.945
as well.

00:20:53.945 --> 00:20:55.320
And we don't need
the adjustment,

00:20:55.320 --> 00:20:58.140
because all of the things
that have been assigned

00:20:58.140 --> 00:21:02.685
to peak vehicles are
being directly related

00:21:02.685 --> 00:21:03.810
to peak vehicles.

00:21:03.810 --> 00:21:05.670
So it's a simple variation.

00:21:05.670 --> 00:21:08.950
And here, we have a
variable annual cost model.

00:21:08.950 --> 00:21:14.560
So these first two have all of
the costs, fixed and variable.

00:21:14.560 --> 00:21:16.020
But for some
applications, you're

00:21:16.020 --> 00:21:17.790
only interested in
variable annual cost.

00:21:17.790 --> 00:21:20.330
And I've given the
example of minor expansion

00:21:20.330 --> 00:21:25.020
in service, where you add
a little bit of service

00:21:25.020 --> 00:21:26.550
or remove a little
bit of service.

00:21:26.550 --> 00:21:29.820
And you wouldn't expect to
incur fixed costs as a result.

00:21:29.820 --> 00:21:33.960
So here, we then only
consider the unit costs

00:21:33.960 --> 00:21:36.960
of the variable portion of
revenue vehicle hours, which

00:21:36.960 --> 00:21:42.120
is 37.13, and 2.57 for
revenue vehicle miles.

00:21:45.380 --> 00:21:49.410
Any questions on
these simple models?

00:21:49.410 --> 00:21:54.600
OK, as I mentioned before,
one of the key weaknesses

00:21:54.600 --> 00:21:57.910
of these models is that they're
not sensitive to time periods.

00:21:57.910 --> 00:22:02.150
So it's much more expensive
to operate sort of on the peak

00:22:02.150 --> 00:22:03.035
than it is off-peak.

00:22:03.035 --> 00:22:07.040
So if you were to use, say,
variable annual cost model

00:22:07.040 --> 00:22:12.080
for bus routes 70
and 78 and now you

00:22:12.080 --> 00:22:14.330
want to expand it
to go to Kendall,

00:22:14.330 --> 00:22:18.590
or Lechmere, or somewhere else,
and you have a greater number

00:22:18.590 --> 00:22:22.820
of revenue vehicle hours than
your revenue vehicle miles,

00:22:22.820 --> 00:22:24.500
if you-- maybe if
you expand service

00:22:24.500 --> 00:22:28.230
proportionally throughout the
peak and off-peak, you're fine.

00:22:28.230 --> 00:22:31.550
But if you only expand
service in the peak or do it

00:22:31.550 --> 00:22:34.160
disproportionately
peak/off-peak,

00:22:34.160 --> 00:22:37.830
then this model will not capture
those differences very well.

00:22:37.830 --> 00:22:42.129
And for that, we need
temporal variational,

00:22:42.129 --> 00:22:42.920
which is our next--

00:22:42.920 --> 00:22:45.500
AUDIENCE: Just a second, but
why wouldn't you capture it?

00:22:45.500 --> 00:22:46.830
Because suppose I had service.

00:22:46.830 --> 00:22:48.260
Suppose I had a bus in the peak.

00:22:48.260 --> 00:22:51.620
So now peak vehicles,
that gets impacted.

00:22:51.620 --> 00:22:55.370
But suppose I take fuel and
I say, OK, there is fuel.

00:22:55.370 --> 00:22:59.310
Fuel affects revenue miles, but
also it affects revenue hours.

00:22:59.310 --> 00:23:03.260
And I put fuel in twice, both
in the hours and the miles.

00:23:03.260 --> 00:23:06.080
Now I can also take
into account the fact

00:23:06.080 --> 00:23:09.660
that the bus is sitting in
traffic and burning fuel

00:23:09.660 --> 00:23:10.670
and also--

00:23:10.670 --> 00:23:12.620
but I'm taking
that into account.

00:23:12.620 --> 00:23:15.370
So why is this model
necessarily [INAUDIBLE]..

00:23:15.890 --> 00:23:17.640
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
So the questions

00:23:17.640 --> 00:23:19.870
why does this model
not adequately capture

00:23:19.870 --> 00:23:22.230
peak versus off-peak costs?

00:23:22.230 --> 00:23:25.130
So it goes back to this
calculating average costs

00:23:25.130 --> 00:23:26.210
by factor.

00:23:26.210 --> 00:23:27.399
So these are averages.

00:23:27.399 --> 00:23:29.690
You're taking averages of
all the vehicles at all times

00:23:29.690 --> 00:23:32.840
of day and dividing by--

00:23:32.840 --> 00:23:35.360
explaining them with
an explanatory variable

00:23:35.360 --> 00:23:38.690
that is not necessarily
was directly causing it.

00:23:38.690 --> 00:23:44.000
And so especially driver costs
are going to vary a lot by sort

00:23:44.000 --> 00:23:45.290
of peak/off-peak.

00:23:45.290 --> 00:23:46.740
And we're taking an average.

00:23:46.740 --> 00:23:49.980
So if you increase service
proportionately, you're fine.

00:23:49.980 --> 00:23:52.850
But the unit cost is not
reflecting the difference

00:23:52.850 --> 00:23:54.200
between peak and off-peak.

00:23:54.200 --> 00:23:56.090
So it's the unit
cost itself more than

00:23:56.090 --> 00:24:00.334
the independent variable
that you put in,

00:24:00.334 --> 00:24:01.500
which is what you're saying.

00:24:01.500 --> 00:24:05.270
You're saying, I can measure the
independent variable precisely,

00:24:05.270 --> 00:24:06.440
so I can plug it in here.

00:24:06.440 --> 00:24:08.875
Well, but your
factor is average.

00:24:08.875 --> 00:24:10.740
AUDIENCE: I see.

00:24:10.740 --> 00:24:13.190
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
So the approach

00:24:13.190 --> 00:24:16.670
of this model, which is an
extension of the first one,

00:24:16.670 --> 00:24:20.780
is to do everything that we
did except for driver costs,

00:24:20.780 --> 00:24:23.990
because these costs are very
sensitive to time of day.

00:24:23.990 --> 00:24:30.450
And for those costs, per
crew costs, we take the day.

00:24:30.450 --> 00:24:32.820
We divide it into
30-minute periods.

00:24:32.820 --> 00:24:34.290
And then we look at all runs.

00:24:34.290 --> 00:24:38.780
Now, a run is what a
driver does in a day.

00:24:38.780 --> 00:24:40.720
That's their shift.

00:24:40.720 --> 00:24:43.130
That's a sequence of
trips that are being

00:24:43.130 --> 00:24:44.950
operated by a single driver.

00:24:44.950 --> 00:24:48.650
And we look at all
runs and all periods.

00:24:48.650 --> 00:24:53.350
And for each period, any
run that is at least this--

00:24:53.350 --> 00:24:55.310
has at least 15
minutes in that period

00:24:55.310 --> 00:24:57.800
gets included in that period.

00:24:57.800 --> 00:25:02.360
And then we compute the
average paid per vehicle hour

00:25:02.360 --> 00:25:05.420
by dividing the daily pay by
the number of vehicle hours

00:25:05.420 --> 00:25:07.500
over all runs in that period.

00:25:07.500 --> 00:25:11.420
So each of these runs is going
to have a different cost.

00:25:11.420 --> 00:25:14.450
Some runs are going to
operate more in the peak.

00:25:14.450 --> 00:25:16.670
And they're going to have
more overtime, for example,

00:25:16.670 --> 00:25:18.430
or more spread penalties.

00:25:18.430 --> 00:25:19.950
And we'll talk about those now.

00:25:19.950 --> 00:25:23.900
And so those runs will
be more expensive.

00:25:23.900 --> 00:25:27.590
Other runs that are straight
are going to be less expensive.

00:25:27.590 --> 00:25:30.680
And you can calculate
an average for each 30-

00:25:30.680 --> 00:25:33.000
or 50-minute period.

00:25:33.000 --> 00:25:35.990
So now we have an
average again, but it's

00:25:35.990 --> 00:25:39.200
by time of day for a
small bucket of time.

00:25:39.200 --> 00:25:43.940
And then for each of those, we
find the minimum, the average,

00:25:43.940 --> 00:25:44.750
and the maximum.

00:25:44.750 --> 00:25:46.760
So we're not only going
to look at averages.

00:25:46.760 --> 00:25:49.820
We're going to also look at
the distribution of costs

00:25:49.820 --> 00:25:52.140
along each period.

00:25:52.140 --> 00:25:56.555
And this is just an
equation for average.

00:25:56.555 --> 00:26:02.660
So what we have here
is the sum over all

00:26:02.660 --> 00:26:06.850
runs in a specific period.

00:26:06.850 --> 00:26:10.790
This is the wage, the total
paid for that run, divided

00:26:10.790 --> 00:26:12.560
by the number of
hours for that run.

00:26:12.560 --> 00:26:15.780
So we compute the average.

00:26:15.780 --> 00:26:20.600
OK, if we look at the driver
requirements for the MBTA back

00:26:20.600 --> 00:26:26.610
in 1983, the early 1980s,
this is what we get.

00:26:26.610 --> 00:26:30.410
So many more
drivers are required

00:26:30.410 --> 00:26:34.490
in the AM peak and the PM peak
than are required off-peak,

00:26:34.490 --> 00:26:39.110
or early in the morning, or late
in the afternoon and evening.

00:26:39.110 --> 00:26:41.209
Why is that?

00:26:41.209 --> 00:26:43.000
We've talked a little
bit about it already.

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:44.291
AUDIENCE: There's more service.

00:26:44.291 --> 00:26:47.064
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
So you provide more service.

00:26:47.064 --> 00:26:48.730
Why do you need to
provide more service?

00:26:48.730 --> 00:26:49.510
AUDIENCE: Because
that's when the--

00:26:49.510 --> 00:26:49.650
AUDIENCE: More demand.

00:26:49.650 --> 00:26:51.290
AUDIENCE: --commuters
are moving.

00:26:51.290 --> 00:26:51.940
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Because there's

00:26:51.940 --> 00:26:53.050
more demand for it, right?

00:26:53.050 --> 00:26:54.850
So if provided the
same level of service,

00:26:54.850 --> 00:26:56.349
then your buses
would be too crowded

00:26:56.349 --> 00:26:58.120
and you would not
deliver enough capacity.

00:26:58.120 --> 00:26:59.430
What else?

00:26:59.430 --> 00:27:01.055
AUDIENCE: They're
also in traffic more.

00:27:01.055 --> 00:27:01.895
So buses are out--

00:27:01.895 --> 00:27:03.520
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
So every trip

00:27:03.520 --> 00:27:07.170
that you run takes longer,
and stuck in traffic.

00:27:07.170 --> 00:27:09.790
And the dwell times are longer.

00:27:09.790 --> 00:27:11.890
OK, so if you need
more, if you need

00:27:11.890 --> 00:27:15.480
to provide more frequent service
and each run that you do,

00:27:15.480 --> 00:27:18.790
each trip that
you run is slower,

00:27:18.790 --> 00:27:22.120
than that means that
you have a greater cycle

00:27:22.120 --> 00:27:25.780
time and a greater
frequency, and therefore,

00:27:25.780 --> 00:27:29.777
a greater vehicle requirement
from your first assignment.

00:27:29.777 --> 00:27:32.110
And of course you need drivers
the drive those vehicles,

00:27:32.110 --> 00:27:34.690
so your driver
requirement also goes up.

00:27:34.690 --> 00:27:37.150
Great, so what's
wrong with the time?

00:27:37.150 --> 00:27:41.200
What's inconvenient about
the timing of the peaks?

00:27:41.200 --> 00:27:42.700
AUDIENCE: They're
eight hours apart.

00:27:42.700 --> 00:27:43.890
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
They are eight hours apart.

00:27:43.890 --> 00:27:45.595
And how long are
shifts typically?

00:27:45.595 --> 00:27:45.890
AUDIENCE: Eight hours.

00:27:45.890 --> 00:27:47.681
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Eight hours long,

00:27:47.681 --> 00:27:50.620
so if we hire someone to
start their shift at 6:00 AM,

00:27:50.620 --> 00:27:52.270
they can't cover the PM peaks.

00:27:52.270 --> 00:27:53.790
They only cover the AM peak.

00:27:53.790 --> 00:27:56.260
OK, so what do we do?

00:27:56.260 --> 00:27:59.140
One option is to
hire part timers.

00:27:59.140 --> 00:28:04.390
So use full-time
employees for the base.

00:28:04.390 --> 00:28:07.880
And then hire part
timers for the peaks.

00:28:07.880 --> 00:28:11.800
That's the least expensive
and most efficient option.

00:28:11.800 --> 00:28:16.360
But unions don't like
it, because if you

00:28:16.360 --> 00:28:19.930
have a high percentage of
part-time drivers, then

00:28:19.930 --> 00:28:24.160
it's not to the benefit
of their union employees.

00:28:24.160 --> 00:28:26.320
If you don't allow
part timers or you

00:28:26.320 --> 00:28:29.050
cap the allowance
on part timers,

00:28:29.050 --> 00:28:33.130
then the agency is required
to hire full-time employees

00:28:33.130 --> 00:28:36.790
to cover the AM and the PM peak.

00:28:36.790 --> 00:28:39.720
And if you only do
that, then that's

00:28:39.720 --> 00:28:42.220
terribly inefficient, because
you're hiring for eight hours.

00:28:42.220 --> 00:28:44.020
Then you can only
operate two or three.

00:28:44.020 --> 00:28:46.540
That's all that you
need that driver for.

00:28:46.540 --> 00:28:49.660
But there is some arrangement.

00:28:49.660 --> 00:28:53.170
You can actually
have shifts that

00:28:53.170 --> 00:28:54.890
have a break in the
middle of the day.

00:28:54.890 --> 00:28:57.100
And these are called
spread shifts.

00:28:57.100 --> 00:29:01.840
So some of these shifts
operate for two or three

00:29:01.840 --> 00:29:04.930
hours in the morning, have
a long break during the day,

00:29:04.930 --> 00:29:08.050
and operate for two or three
hours in the afternoon.

00:29:08.050 --> 00:29:13.250
And often, these shifts
are paid a spread penalty.

00:29:13.250 --> 00:29:17.620
So in this example, what
we have in white here

00:29:17.620 --> 00:29:22.700
are shifts that last between
10 hours and 11 hours.

00:29:22.700 --> 00:29:25.840
So the spread is the difference
between the check-out time

00:29:25.840 --> 00:29:27.910
and the check-in time.

00:29:27.910 --> 00:29:36.360
And shifts in white here have a
spread between 10 and 11 hours.

00:29:36.360 --> 00:29:42.720
Those drivers are paid a
50% premium for any hours

00:29:42.720 --> 00:29:45.900
above 8 hours.

00:29:45.900 --> 00:29:48.750
And then there are
these other shifts that

00:29:48.750 --> 00:29:51.580
are between 11 and 13 hours.

00:29:51.580 --> 00:29:55.770
So 11, 12 in dark
gray, and 12 and 13

00:29:55.770 --> 00:29:59.790
shaded diagonally, these
shifts are paid 100%.

00:29:59.790 --> 00:30:04.790
So they're paid double for
any hours in excess of the--

00:30:04.790 --> 00:30:08.130
I guess in excess
of 11, in this case.

00:30:08.130 --> 00:30:10.740
So that's going
to drive costs up,

00:30:10.740 --> 00:30:14.520
because if you look at the
total pay for that shift

00:30:14.520 --> 00:30:21.380
over the day, then the
unit pay per hour for each

00:30:21.380 --> 00:30:24.140
of those drivers is higher.

00:30:24.140 --> 00:30:26.917
And if you look at any
time slice of the day,

00:30:26.917 --> 00:30:29.000
peaks are going to have
many more of those drivers

00:30:29.000 --> 00:30:30.400
than off-peak.

00:30:30.400 --> 00:30:33.710
So the average across the
drivers on any bucket of time

00:30:33.710 --> 00:30:36.965
that is 30 minutes wide
is going to be higher.

00:30:36.965 --> 00:30:39.050
AUDIENCE: Sorry, could you
