00:38:52.615 --> 00:38:53.115
so--

00:38:53.115 --> 00:38:54.390
AUDIENCE: But I
guess, even combined,

00:38:54.390 --> 00:38:56.431
like, wouldn't you want
to use the max or the min

00:38:56.431 --> 00:38:58.644
because it's incremental?

00:38:58.644 --> 00:39:00.060
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
The idea

00:39:00.060 --> 00:39:05.222
is that, if you increase
things proportionally, then

00:39:05.222 --> 00:39:07.180
you're going to have the
same mix that you have

00:39:07.180 --> 00:39:11.770
now but a little more each.

00:39:11.770 --> 00:39:16.450
If you add service both peak and
off-peak in proportion, which

00:39:16.450 --> 00:39:19.060
means that, if there is twice
as much peak service, then

00:39:19.060 --> 00:39:22.000
you're going to have twice
much more peak service,

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:26.570
then you're going to have the
same distribution of spread

00:39:26.570 --> 00:39:30.330
penalties, and therefore,
the same average costs.

00:39:30.330 --> 00:39:33.060
But now we go to the
next question, which

00:39:33.060 --> 00:39:36.687
is, increases in peak period
services only, which of these

00:39:36.687 --> 00:39:37.270
would you use?

00:39:40.490 --> 00:39:41.417
AUDIENCE: The max.

00:39:41.417 --> 00:39:43.250
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
We're hearing max.

00:39:43.250 --> 00:39:46.130
And I assume for
peak, max for peak?

00:39:46.130 --> 00:39:46.755
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:39:46.755 --> 00:39:48.504
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Any other ideas?

00:39:48.504 --> 00:39:49.734
AUDIENCE: Peak average.

00:39:49.734 --> 00:39:52.410
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Peak average, two ideas--

00:39:52.410 --> 00:39:53.370
OK, let's debate.

00:39:58.864 --> 00:40:00.280
AUDIENCE: All
right, so basically,

00:40:00.280 --> 00:40:03.490
if we're increasing in
the peak period only,

00:40:03.490 --> 00:40:09.830
we're going to have to do
more of these spread shifts

00:40:09.830 --> 00:40:10.330
to do that.

00:40:10.330 --> 00:40:11.579
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Yes.

00:40:11.579 --> 00:40:13.784
AUDIENCE: And those are
our most expensive shifts.

00:40:13.784 --> 00:40:15.825
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Yes, are you convinced?

00:40:15.825 --> 00:40:16.825
AUDIENCE: I'm convinced.

00:40:16.825 --> 00:40:23.950
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: OK,
good so great, so $45 right,

00:40:23.950 --> 00:40:25.760
the maximum of the peak--

00:40:25.760 --> 00:40:29.760
what if it's a decrease
in peak period service?

00:40:29.760 --> 00:40:32.740
So now we're coming
back here and we're only

00:40:32.740 --> 00:40:37.360
taking the top of the top off
and we're not giving anything

00:40:37.360 --> 00:40:40.035
to the off-peak [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:40.035 --> 00:40:41.306
AUDIENCE: The inverse.

00:40:41.306 --> 00:40:42.281
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:40:42.281 --> 00:40:43.780
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Same, 45--

00:40:43.780 --> 00:40:44.488
AUDIENCE: Maximum

00:40:44.488 --> 00:40:46.940
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
--going down now, OK, great--

00:40:46.940 --> 00:40:52.400
OK, increases in off-peak
period services only,

00:40:52.400 --> 00:40:54.830
so now we're leaving
the peak where it is.

00:40:54.830 --> 00:40:58.140
And we're decreasing service
off-peak-- so here and maybe

00:40:58.140 --> 00:41:00.919
at night.

00:41:00.919 --> 00:41:02.210
AUDIENCE: Increasing, you said?

00:41:02.210 --> 00:41:03.320
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Decreasing--

00:41:03.320 --> 00:41:04.315
is it decreasing or increasing?

00:41:04.315 --> 00:41:04.590
AUDIENCE: Increase.

00:41:04.590 --> 00:41:05.381
AUDIENCE: Increase.

00:41:05.381 --> 00:41:09.086
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Let's start with increasing.

00:41:09.086 --> 00:41:13.000
AUDIENCE: Then maybe
minimum in off-peak?

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:14.640
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
OK, that's

00:41:14.640 --> 00:41:17.220
actually the high end
of what it could be.

00:41:17.220 --> 00:41:20.100
So of the cells
here, yes, that's

00:41:20.100 --> 00:41:21.496
the one that you should pick.

00:41:21.496 --> 00:41:24.570
You should use the
minimum off-peak.

00:41:24.570 --> 00:41:27.600
But it could actually
be closer to 0.

00:41:27.600 --> 00:41:30.020
If you're depending on the
cost structure and the spread

00:41:30.020 --> 00:41:32.520
penalties, you will
be able to convert

00:41:32.520 --> 00:41:35.160
some of the drivers that
are peak to spread--

00:41:35.160 --> 00:41:36.390
to a non-spread shift.

00:41:36.390 --> 00:41:39.570
So you'll get straight
shifts from these drivers.

00:41:39.570 --> 00:41:42.210
And that may actually
compensate so much

00:41:42.210 --> 00:41:45.050
that it's a free conversion.

00:41:48.050 --> 00:41:54.476
So what about decreases in
off-peak period service?

00:41:58.940 --> 00:42:03.020
So now we are actually
decreasing the off-peak

00:42:03.020 --> 00:42:05.400
and leaving everything the same.

00:42:05.400 --> 00:42:08.840
So what two things happen?

00:42:08.840 --> 00:42:10.940
Presumably, off-peak
services are straight runs.

00:42:10.940 --> 00:42:12.380
They're not spread.

00:42:12.380 --> 00:42:15.710
So if you remove those
but keep the peak level

00:42:15.710 --> 00:42:19.430
operation the same, then for
any of those that you remove,

00:42:19.430 --> 00:42:20.030
you have to--

00:42:20.030 --> 00:42:20.685
AUDIENCE: Add in
the most expensive--

00:42:20.685 --> 00:42:23.330
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: --add
in the most expensive ones.

00:42:23.330 --> 00:42:25.785
So what is the net effect?

00:42:25.785 --> 00:42:26.660
AUDIENCE: Adding $15.

00:42:29.495 --> 00:42:31.120
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
It's probably

00:42:31.120 --> 00:42:36.629
going to be close to 0 again
because of this effect.

00:42:36.629 --> 00:42:37.920
AUDIENCE: But can you explain--

00:42:37.920 --> 00:42:39.628
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
And again, this

00:42:39.628 --> 00:42:42.234
depends on the specific
costs for the labor agreement

00:42:42.234 --> 00:42:43.900
and the spread penalties
and everything.

00:42:43.900 --> 00:42:45.590
But it gives you an idea.

00:42:45.590 --> 00:42:49.141
So if you only decrease
off-peak service--

00:42:49.141 --> 00:42:51.410
AUDIENCE: You're
getting rid of those.

00:42:51.410 --> 00:42:53.785
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
--then you have to remove a few

00:42:53.785 --> 00:42:56.950
of the straight runs and
not pay them the full day,

00:42:56.950 --> 00:42:58.610
but you have to then get--

00:42:58.610 --> 00:43:03.830
you have to convert some of
the existing spread runs to--

00:43:03.830 --> 00:43:05.230
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] straight.

00:43:05.230 --> 00:43:07.810
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
--from straight to spread.

00:43:07.810 --> 00:43:10.900
AUDIENCE: Well wait, why
is it at a cost of 0 then?

00:43:10.900 --> 00:43:12.850
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Because you--

00:43:12.850 --> 00:43:17.820
even though you are reducing
the number of driver hours,

00:43:17.820 --> 00:43:21.430
you will increase the proportion
of the most expensive ones

00:43:21.430 --> 00:43:22.954
only in the peak.

00:43:22.954 --> 00:43:25.120
AUDIENCE: So you might not
wind up saving any money.

00:43:25.120 --> 00:43:25.980
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Exactly.

00:43:25.980 --> 00:43:27.939
AUDIENCE: Where would
you put it in the matrix?

00:43:27.939 --> 00:43:30.230
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Well, it's not in the matrix.

00:43:30.230 --> 00:43:32.560
But if anything, you would
look at off-peak minimum.

00:43:32.560 --> 00:43:34.826
But it's going to be in
the range of 0 to 30.

00:43:34.826 --> 00:43:36.700
And again, depending on
the specific numbers,

00:43:36.700 --> 00:43:39.670
it could even be that
you have to pay more.

00:43:39.670 --> 00:43:41.377
Or many things can happen.

00:43:41.377 --> 00:43:42.210
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:43:42.210 --> 00:43:44.585
AUDIENCE: --thinking it was
going to be like the occupant

00:43:44.585 --> 00:43:45.907
minimum and the peak maximum.

00:43:45.907 --> 00:43:47.740
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Yeah, it could be.

00:43:47.740 --> 00:43:49.240
That's a good idea.

00:43:49.240 --> 00:43:51.010
But again, it depends
