It should be, "see page 6."

00:44:25.650 --> 00:44:29.630
OK, so from page six, the total
fixed cost to be allocated

00:44:29.630 --> 00:44:34.730
is $44.6 million.

00:44:34.730 --> 00:44:37.770
And that is the sum of--

00:44:37.770 --> 00:44:39.472
we want to allocate fixed costs.

00:44:39.472 --> 00:44:40.930
So that is the sum
of all the fixed

00:44:40.930 --> 00:44:42.460
costs that appear on page six.

00:44:42.460 --> 00:44:45.790
There's 5.7, 3, and 35.9.

00:44:45.790 --> 00:44:48.970
That adds up to 44.6.

00:44:48.970 --> 00:44:54.380
And now we have here number of
buses operating on the peak,

00:44:54.380 --> 00:44:56.330
on the base, on the
evening, Saturday

00:44:56.330 --> 00:44:58.250
and Sunday, the
number of hours--

00:44:58.250 --> 00:45:01.820
so peak average,
4.5, 6 base hours,

00:45:01.820 --> 00:45:06.050
4 evening hours for a total
of 14.5 hours per week day,

00:45:06.050 --> 00:45:10.010
12 hours operating Saturday,
12 hours operating Sunday.

00:45:10.010 --> 00:45:12.470
And the objective
of this model is

00:45:12.470 --> 00:45:16.310
to take the fixed costs
incurred by the agency

00:45:16.310 --> 00:45:22.460
and allocate them
to vehicle hours.

00:45:22.460 --> 00:45:24.180
So let's do that.

00:45:24.180 --> 00:45:25.620
We have to do this allocation.

00:45:25.620 --> 00:45:29.690
And we can start with--

00:45:29.690 --> 00:45:32.720
one way of looking at this
is, these evening buses,

00:45:32.720 --> 00:45:36.440
250 evening buses are
also operating in the base

00:45:36.440 --> 00:45:38.840
and in the peak.

00:45:38.840 --> 00:45:41.720
Then there's an
additional 125 buses

00:45:41.720 --> 00:45:46.410
that are operating only in
the base and at Saturdays,

00:45:46.410 --> 00:45:48.360
during Saturdays.

00:45:48.360 --> 00:45:50.760
And then there's an
additional 400 buses

00:45:50.760 --> 00:45:54.640
that are operating only in
the peak during the weekday.

00:45:54.640 --> 00:46:00.450
So let's allocate costs to
the 250, the additional 125,

00:46:00.450 --> 00:46:04.330
and the additional 400 according
to how long they operate

00:46:04.330 --> 00:46:07.300
and how much it costs
based on the unit costs

00:46:07.300 --> 00:46:10.370
that we calculated
in this example.

00:46:10.370 --> 00:46:15.760
So we start with 250 buses
across all time periods.

00:46:15.760 --> 00:46:18.100
What's the share of fixed
cost to be allocated to them?

00:46:18.100 --> 00:46:19.040
It's 32%.

00:46:19.040 --> 00:46:22.150
It's 250 buses divided
by the total number

00:46:22.150 --> 00:46:24.580
of buses, which is 775.

00:46:24.580 --> 00:46:26.520
That's 32%.

00:46:26.520 --> 00:46:29.660
32% of the total cost
is $14.4 million.

00:46:29.660 --> 00:46:33.970
That's how much money we want
to allocate to these buses.

00:46:33.970 --> 00:46:37.610
And how many bus hours are
operated in the whole year?

00:46:37.610 --> 00:46:40.180
Well, there's 250 buses.

00:46:40.180 --> 00:46:42.580
And we want to add
up the hours operated

00:46:42.580 --> 00:46:45.040
during weekdays, during
Saturdays, and during Sundays

00:46:45.040 --> 00:46:46.070
for the whole week.

00:46:46.070 --> 00:46:48.410
So there are
roughly 250 weekdays

00:46:48.410 --> 00:46:51.460
in a year, 58 Saturdays,
and 57 Sundays.

00:46:51.460 --> 00:46:54.010
Those add up to 365 days.

00:46:54.010 --> 00:46:56.810
And there are 14.5
hours during the weekday

00:46:56.810 --> 00:46:58.570
and 12 on the weekends.

00:46:58.570 --> 00:46:59.795
So we add those up.

00:46:59.795 --> 00:47:01.690
We multiply by the
number of buses.

00:47:01.690 --> 00:47:08.560
And we get 1.25 million bus
hours for the whole year.

00:47:08.560 --> 00:47:13.360
And if we divide
the $14.4 million

00:47:13.360 --> 00:47:17.500
by 1.25 million bus hours,
we get an average cost

00:47:17.500 --> 00:47:20.650
per bus hour of $11.52.

00:47:20.650 --> 00:47:24.430
And that's the base, which is
the only thing that applies

00:47:24.430 --> 00:47:26.290
in the evening and Sundays.

00:47:26.290 --> 00:47:28.540
And it is a portion
of what applies

00:47:28.540 --> 00:47:33.080
in Saturday, weekday days,
and peak, so only a portion.

00:47:33.080 --> 00:47:37.420
So now let's move to
the next 125 buses

00:47:37.420 --> 00:47:41.890
operating on all time periods
except Sundays and weekday

00:47:41.890 --> 00:47:43.060
evenings.

00:47:43.060 --> 00:47:45.820
So how much money do
we have to allocate?

00:47:45.820 --> 00:47:51.250
The $44.6 million total divided
by the additional 125 buses

00:47:51.250 --> 00:47:53.110
divided by the total
number of buses.

00:47:53.110 --> 00:47:55.930
That's $7.2 million.

00:47:55.930 --> 00:48:00.040
How many total bus hours are
operated by those 125 buses?

00:48:00.040 --> 00:48:05.200
Well, this is 10.5
hours excluding

00:48:05.200 --> 00:48:10.210
the evening during the weekdays
times 250 weekdays plus the 12

00:48:10.210 --> 00:48:13.390
hours on Saturdays
times the 58 Saturdays.

00:48:13.390 --> 00:48:16.630
So that's 0.42
million bus hours.

00:48:16.630 --> 00:48:23.260
And 7.2 divided by 0.42
is $17.14 average cost

00:48:23.260 --> 00:48:24.220
per bus hour.

00:48:24.220 --> 00:48:25.355
Do you follow?

00:48:25.355 --> 00:48:27.350
Any questions on this?

00:48:27.350 --> 00:48:29.350
OK, now let's do the peak.

00:48:29.350 --> 00:48:31.210
That's the most expensive part.

00:48:31.210 --> 00:48:33.690
So how much do we
have to allocate?

00:48:33.690 --> 00:48:34.750
It's $23 million.

00:48:34.750 --> 00:48:35.770
How do we get that?

00:48:35.770 --> 00:48:44.800
44.6 total times
400 divided by 725.

00:48:44.800 --> 00:48:47.950
And how many annual bus
hours do we need to--

00:48:47.950 --> 00:48:49.600
do we operate during the peak?

00:48:49.600 --> 00:48:54.130
It's 400 additional buses only
in the peak times 4.5 hours

00:48:54.130 --> 00:48:57.310
of the peak times 250 weekdays.

00:48:57.310 --> 00:49:00.610
And that's 0.45 million hours.

00:49:00.610 --> 00:49:07.270
And 23 million by 0.45
is $51.11 average cost

00:49:07.270 --> 00:49:10.110
per bus hour, or per peak
bus hour, in this case.

00:49:10.110 --> 00:49:17.560
OK, so now we have unit
costs for peak, for the base,

00:49:17.560 --> 00:49:21.430
and then the off-peak, for
the evenings' and Sundays'

00:49:21.430 --> 00:49:24.110
operation, which is great.

00:49:24.110 --> 00:49:29.530
So the variable vehicle
cost was $37.13.

00:49:29.530 --> 00:49:32.020
We had calculated that
from the previous model

00:49:32.020 --> 00:49:34.030
that you can find on page six.

00:49:34.030 --> 00:49:37.870
And now we can
adjust these costs

00:49:37.870 --> 00:49:41.150
by time period, which
is what we want to do.

00:49:41.150 --> 00:49:44.540
We want to have a model that
is sensitive to time periods.

00:49:44.540 --> 00:49:50.320
So for Sunday evening service,
we will increase the $37.13

00:49:50.320 --> 00:49:52.750
by $11.52.

00:49:52.750 --> 00:49:54.670
For Saturday and
weekday service,

00:49:54.670 --> 00:49:58.690
we want to increase the cost,
the base cost of $37.13,

00:49:58.690 --> 00:50:01.300
by $13.97.

00:50:01.300 --> 00:50:07.420
And for weekday peak, we want
to increase it by $32.86.

00:50:07.420 --> 00:50:11.110
And notice that when we look
at Saturday and weekday,

00:50:11.110 --> 00:50:13.630
we have to combine
the two unit costs,

00:50:13.630 --> 00:50:18.280
because we have a
portion of Saturday

00:50:18.280 --> 00:50:23.410
and weekday-based service
is from the first 375 buses.

00:50:23.410 --> 00:50:25.990
And the portion of it is from
the additional more expensive

00:50:25.990 --> 00:50:27.540
125 buses.

00:50:27.540 --> 00:50:29.560
And when we do peak,
the same thing applies.

00:50:29.560 --> 00:50:35.590
So we start with the 250
base buses at $11.52.

00:50:35.590 --> 00:50:38.260
Then we have 125 at $17.14.

00:50:38.260 --> 00:50:40.510
And then we have the peak
of the peak buses, which

00:50:40.510 --> 00:50:43.570
are 400 times the unit
cost for those buses, which

00:50:43.570 --> 00:50:45.230
is much higher.

00:50:45.230 --> 00:50:47.740
And that's the total
cost, the total unit cost

00:50:47.740 --> 00:50:51.230
for a weekday peak service.

00:50:51.230 --> 00:50:52.010
Questions on this?

00:50:55.090 --> 00:50:56.235
You have a question, Eli?

