associated with peak vehicles.

00:51:30.730 --> 00:51:33.610
So that was the first example.

00:51:33.610 --> 00:51:37.990
We also had in that page a
variable cost model, which

00:51:37.990 --> 00:51:39.780
only accounts for
variable costs,

00:51:39.780 --> 00:51:42.340
so it excludes fixed costs.

00:51:42.340 --> 00:51:44.920
And now we can look at
the peak period model

00:51:44.920 --> 00:51:46.150
and off-peak period model.

00:51:46.150 --> 00:51:57.790
So we make an adjustment
to the first model, which--

00:51:57.790 --> 00:52:01.700
to this variable cost
model with the unit

00:52:01.700 --> 00:52:02.920
cost that we just calculated.

00:52:02.920 --> 00:52:08.800
So if we take the $37.13
of revenue vehicle hours

00:52:08.800 --> 00:52:11.200
that was in our initial
variable cost model

00:52:11.200 --> 00:52:17.590
and we add the unit cost
for peak revenue hours,

00:52:17.590 --> 00:52:26.360
which is $32.86
from right here--

00:52:26.360 --> 00:52:30.200
so that's the weekday
peak service unit cost--

00:52:30.200 --> 00:52:34.370
then we get $69.99.

00:52:34.370 --> 00:52:38.570
Now that becomes our
unit cost in the peak.

00:52:38.570 --> 00:52:46.280
And we have the 2.41.

00:52:46.280 --> 00:52:48.810
Give me a second here.

00:52:48.810 --> 00:52:51.600
That comes from page
six directly, I believe.

00:52:54.430 --> 00:52:58.530
Yes, so that's the
combination of 2.27 and 0.14.

00:52:58.530 --> 00:53:03.960
Because we're not counting
the temporal difference

00:53:03.960 --> 00:53:06.830
on peak vehicle or
revenue vehicle miles.

00:53:06.830 --> 00:53:10.310
We're only doing it for
revenue vehicle hours.

00:53:10.310 --> 00:53:11.810
It's for driver cost.

00:53:11.810 --> 00:53:14.730
And driver costs were associated
with hours, not miles.

00:53:14.730 --> 00:53:17.770
So that stays the same.

00:53:17.770 --> 00:53:21.450
So this is our full
annual peak cost model.

00:53:21.450 --> 00:53:24.810
And if we want to increase
peak-only service,

00:53:24.810 --> 00:53:26.550
we use this model,
not the other one.

00:53:26.550 --> 00:53:28.980
And it will reflect
more faithfully

00:53:28.980 --> 00:53:31.032
what the costs will be.

00:53:31.032 --> 00:53:32.740
We can do the same
with off-peak service.

00:53:32.740 --> 00:53:37.140
So we take the $37.13.

00:53:37.140 --> 00:53:42.060
And we can add the combination
of the portion of it

00:53:42.060 --> 00:53:46.170
that is $11.52 and the
portion of it that is $13.97.

00:53:46.170 --> 00:53:47.290
Let's do that.

00:53:47.290 --> 00:53:49.162
So let me have--

00:53:49.162 --> 00:53:51.510
let's do that on the board
so that we have the example.

00:53:54.790 --> 00:54:17.440
So for off-peak period
model, we start out

00:54:17.440 --> 00:54:26.080
with the base cost of $37.13.

00:54:26.080 --> 00:54:32.380
And then we add $11.52.

00:54:32.380 --> 00:54:35.800
And that's going to apply
only for the fraction

00:54:35.800 --> 00:54:44.780
of off-peak hours that are sort
of Sunday and weekday evening.

00:54:44.780 --> 00:54:49.870
So if we go back to $11.52, this
is Sunday and evening service

00:54:49.870 --> 00:54:51.050
only.

00:54:51.050 --> 00:54:53.630
So the question is, how many
Sunday and evening service

00:54:53.630 --> 00:54:55.020
hours are there in a whole year?

00:55:00.830 --> 00:55:02.900
The proportion is this
one that I'm writing here,

00:55:02.900 --> 00:55:12.890
1684 divided by 3,880.

00:55:12.890 --> 00:55:17.580
And I'll calculate
that too in a second.

00:55:17.580 --> 00:55:25.640
We also want to add the
other cost, which is $13.97.

00:55:25.640 --> 00:55:41.060
And the proportion of that
is 2,196 divide by 3,880.

00:55:41.060 --> 00:55:54.630
So that's 37.13 plus
about 5 plus about 7.91.

00:55:54.630 --> 00:56:01.800
And that comes out to 50.04.

00:56:01.800 --> 00:56:09.210
OK, so where do we get
1,684 and 2,196 from?

00:56:09.210 --> 00:56:10.710
It's similar to before, right?

00:56:10.710 --> 00:56:12.960
We just count how
many hours there are.

00:56:12.960 --> 00:56:16.270
So let's just do it quickly
here for the record.

00:56:16.270 --> 00:56:20.820
So let's just compute
the bottom one, actually.

00:56:20.820 --> 00:56:22.650
And you'll get the
idea for the others,

00:56:22.650 --> 00:56:25.040
because it doesn't make
sense to do all of them.

00:56:25.040 --> 00:56:33.670
So off peak hours--

00:56:33.670 --> 00:56:41.700
so we have 10 off-peak hours in
the weekday times 250 weekdays

00:56:41.700 --> 00:56:44.550
per year plus--

00:56:44.550 --> 00:56:47.307
so this is weekdays--

00:56:50.440 --> 00:56:53.740
plus 12 hours on Saturdays.

00:56:53.740 --> 00:56:55.210
And we said there are 7--

00:56:55.210 --> 00:56:56.770
or 58 Saturdays per year--

00:57:00.400 --> 00:57:05.220
plus 12 hours on Sundays, and
we said 57 Sundays per year.

00:57:08.210 --> 00:57:22.230
And that comes out
to 3,880 hours.

00:57:22.230 --> 00:57:28.122
So that's combinations of these
to get the 1,684 and the 2,196.

00:57:28.122 --> 00:57:29.460
Yeah?

00:57:29.460 --> 00:57:34.050
AUDIENCE: So for
the 1,684, that's

00:57:34.050 --> 00:57:37.159
Sunday evening service, right?

00:57:37.159 --> 00:57:39.200
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Right, so yes, exactly.

00:57:39.200 --> 00:57:41.500
So that's Sunday
and evenings, right.

00:57:41.500 --> 00:57:44.180
AUDIENCE: And then the other
is Saturday and weekend base?

00:57:44.180 --> 00:57:45.805
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Yes, exactly.

00:57:52.430 --> 00:57:55.550
So did people follow
this allocation example?

00:57:55.550 --> 00:57:59.570
So what we're doing is taking--
dividing the day into periods.

00:57:59.570 --> 00:58:02.120
Some periods, we recognize
are more expensive than others

00:58:02.120 --> 00:58:03.020
throughout.

00:58:06.080 --> 00:58:07.080
Now, we have fixed cost.

00:58:07.080 --> 00:58:10.710
And we want to allocate
them across periods.

00:58:10.710 --> 00:58:13.220
And we want to allocate
more cost to the peak,

00:58:13.220 --> 00:58:15.440
because that sort of costs more.

00:58:15.440 --> 00:58:20.840
So we then use these
unit costs to--

00:58:20.840 --> 00:58:24.020
and we count how many
hours we provide off-peak

00:58:24.020 --> 00:58:25.040
and during the peak.

00:58:25.040 --> 00:58:30.620
And we do things in proportions
to that, essentially.

00:58:30.620 --> 00:58:32.307
These are not the
only cost models

00:58:32.307 --> 00:58:33.390
that you can come up with.

00:58:33.390 --> 00:58:35.840
These are not the only
ways of allocating cost.

00:58:35.840 --> 00:58:38.150
But they provide an
example of how you

00:58:38.150 --> 00:58:39.770
can go about allocating costs.

00:58:39.770 --> 00:58:43.520
Allocating cost is a science.

00:58:43.520 --> 00:58:44.450
It's also an art.

00:58:44.450 --> 00:58:48.350
And you encounter
it in agencies,

00:58:48.350 --> 00:58:51.245
because you have these huge
budgets, and huge expenditures.

00:58:51.245 --> 00:58:55.400
And many projects require
you to allocate to a portion

00:58:55.400 --> 00:58:56.750
or allocate costs.

00:58:56.750 --> 00:58:59.120
And if you want to have a
cost model, you have to do it,

00:58:59.120 --> 00:59:01.240
because your cost
model should reflect

00:59:01.240 --> 00:59:07.980
these different variables,
explanatory variables.

00:59:07.980 --> 00:59:10.830
The third and last type of model
that we are going to discuss

00:59:10.830 --> 00:59:16.500
is the incremental
fixed variable model.

00:59:16.500 --> 00:59:19.120
It's somewhat similar to
the ones that we saw before,

00:59:19.120 --> 00:59:24.540
but now we classify costs as
being variable, semi-variable,

00:59:24.540 --> 00:59:26.080
and fixed.

00:59:26.080 --> 00:59:29.235
So we have a little more

00:59:29.235 --> 00:59:30.570
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:59:30.570 --> 00:59:31.200
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
--precision--

00:59:31.200 --> 00:59:33.180
AUDIENCE: ----[INAUDIBLE]
marked by--

00:59:33.180 --> 00:59:36.500
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: --a
little more precision in how--

00:59:36.500 --> 00:59:38.940
in what we consider
fixed or variable.

00:59:38.940 --> 00:59:40.830
We also have the same
explanatory variables

00:59:40.830 --> 00:59:43.280
that we had before, so
vehicle hours, vehicle miles,

00:59:43.280 --> 00:59:44.850
and peak vehicles.

00:59:44.850 --> 00:59:47.480
So now, the combination
of these are

00:59:47.480 --> 00:59:50.350
nine different
explanatory variables.

00:59:50.350 --> 00:59:53.760
And we do the same thing
as we have done before.

00:59:53.760 --> 00:59:55.660
We have a schedule of expenses.

00:59:55.660 --> 00:59:58.330
These are our accounts
in your ledger,

00:59:58.330 --> 01:00:01.230
so crew wages, vehicle
servicing, fuel, tires,

01:00:01.230 --> 01:00:05.460
insurance, traffic stuff,
things like publicity, and rent,

01:00:05.460 --> 01:00:06.510
and building maintenance.

01:00:06.510 --> 01:00:07.676
Everything is included here.

01:00:07.676 --> 01:00:11.220
So all of your budget is going
to fall into some category.

01:00:11.220 --> 01:00:12.960
It's divided among
these categories.

01:00:12.960 --> 01:00:21.030
So now you decide,
for each of these,

01:00:21.030 --> 01:00:23.040
which of these three
resources apply

01:00:23.040 --> 01:00:26.340
and which cost type you
consider this to be.

01:00:26.340 --> 01:00:29.000
So for example, crew
wages, let's associate

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:30.870
that with bus hours,
as we did before.

01:00:30.870 --> 01:00:32.820
And that's fully variable.

01:00:32.820 --> 01:00:35.520
So that, we should
feel comfortable with.

01:00:35.520 --> 01:00:41.380
Things like building utilities,
that shouldn't be variable.

01:00:41.380 --> 01:00:42.400
So that's a fixed cost.

01:00:42.400 --> 01:00:44.108
And we'll associate
that with peak buses,

01:00:44.108 --> 01:00:46.420
because peak buses
is the one that we

01:00:46.420 --> 01:00:49.780
say is a good proxy for
how big the agency is.

01:00:49.780 --> 01:00:54.590
So peak buses is, again, like
agency size, if you will.

01:00:54.590 --> 01:00:57.050
So then there are
things in the middle.

01:00:57.050 --> 01:01:01.930
So publicity, well,
semi-variable, because if you--

01:01:01.930 --> 01:01:03.970
so the extent that
you increase service,

01:01:03.970 --> 01:01:06.345
there is going to be some
amount of additional publicity.

01:01:06.345 --> 01:01:09.430
It's not going to be
necessarily a linear proportion

01:01:09.430 --> 01:01:12.590
increase with as you-- you
know, we add one more bus,

01:01:12.590 --> 01:01:18.760
then you have that much more
marketing or publicity expense.

01:01:18.760 --> 01:01:21.850
Some of those expenses are
having an office and staff, so

01:01:21.850 --> 01:01:24.730
some salaries, so
that portion is fixed.

01:01:24.730 --> 01:01:26.530
But then there is
extra space that you

01:01:26.530 --> 01:01:30.020
have to cover on each additional
bus, so that part is variable.

01:01:30.020 --> 01:01:32.320
So now we have a
semi-variable cost.

01:01:32.320 --> 01:01:37.270
And you can associate that,
in this case, with peak buses,

01:01:37.270 --> 01:01:39.460
because for each peak
bus you have, then

01:01:39.460 --> 01:01:43.990
that's how many buses you
have to plaster with ads.

01:01:43.990 --> 01:01:45.730
That gives you an example.

01:01:45.730 --> 01:01:47.800
So you can go through
each of these.

01:01:47.800 --> 01:01:50.830
Again, this requires judgment,
and therefore, each person

01:01:50.830 --> 01:01:52.450
may do it slightly differently.

01:01:52.450 --> 01:01:55.930
But you use a schedule.

01:01:55.930 --> 01:01:59.200
And you then build your--

01:01:59.200 --> 01:02:01.300
you calculate your unit
costs, much like we

01:02:01.300 --> 01:02:03.370
did with the earlier examples.

01:02:03.370 --> 01:02:04.959
And you then apply the model.

01:02:04.959 --> 01:02:06.250
But now we have more precision.

01:02:06.250 --> 01:02:12.190
So if you have some
kind of new expense,

01:02:12.190 --> 01:02:15.220
or you decide you're going
to save some money somehow,

01:02:15.220 --> 01:02:18.490
then you decide,
what-- how am I going

01:02:18.490 --> 01:02:20.740
to spend less or spend more?

01:02:20.740 --> 01:02:23.481
Would that be a variable,
semi-variable, or fixed cost?

01:02:23.481 --> 01:02:25.855
Would I associate that with
vehicle hours, vehicle miles,

01:02:25.855 --> 01:02:27.310
or peak vehicles?

01:02:27.310 --> 01:02:29.320
And then you would
use that unit cost

01:02:29.320 --> 01:02:35.800
to bring the total costs
up or down from the agency.

01:02:35.800 --> 01:02:38.080
Even more detailed
models, you could just

01:02:38.080 --> 01:02:43.840
go by expense category and do
your engineering-style sort

01:02:43.840 --> 01:02:47.170
of budget if you want
to really calculate

01:02:47.170 --> 01:02:48.670
exactly how much
cost you'll save,

01:02:48.670 --> 01:02:53.240
or exactly how much
extra cost you'll incur.

01:02:53.240 --> 01:02:56.750
But these cost models
are applied more--

01:02:56.750 --> 01:02:59.360
a little more
bluntly in projects

01:02:59.360 --> 01:03:01.250
where you are
evaluating, especially

01:03:01.250 --> 01:03:03.775
at an early stage,
what it would cost.

01:03:03.775 --> 01:03:05.150
And you have
different scenarios.

01:03:05.150 --> 01:03:08.832
And you want to quickly
know how much it would cost.

01:03:08.832 --> 01:03:11.550
OK, so questions
on cost modeling?

01:03:16.480 --> 01:03:17.710
No questions on cost--

01:03:17.710 --> 01:03:18.680
yeah, one question?

01:03:18.680 --> 01:03:23.330
AUDIENCE: So in this case, you
would have more reliability

01:03:23.330 --> 01:03:28.040
on the proportion of
each expense assigned

01:03:28.040 --> 01:03:29.044
to each category?

01:03:29.044 --> 01:03:30.710
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Yeah, so you--

01:03:30.710 --> 01:03:33.620
essentially, you're lumping
things a little less.

01:03:33.620 --> 01:03:34.650
You have more variables.

01:03:34.650 --> 01:03:36.545
So your unit costs
are more precise.

01:03:40.450 --> 01:03:45.070
And I think the ability to move
to more sophisticated models

01:03:45.070 --> 01:03:49.680
is increasing now that
everything is computer-based.

01:03:49.680 --> 01:03:51.680
[INAUDIBLE], you had a question?

01:03:51.680 --> 01:03:52.600
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:03:53.365 --> 01:03:54.240
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:03:54.240 --> 01:03:54.906
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Oh, the three of you

01:03:54.906 --> 01:03:55.910
had a question.

01:03:55.910 --> 01:03:56.640
No, not you?

01:03:56.640 --> 01:03:57.140
OK.

01:03:57.140 --> 01:03:57.610
AUDIENCE: I had a question.

01:03:57.610 --> 01:03:58.570
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
OK, Ethan.

01:03:58.570 --> 01:04:00.550
AUDIENCE: Back on
Slide 11, you said

01:04:00.550 --> 01:04:04.210
it's possible that
reducing driver

01:04:04.210 --> 01:04:09.790
hours in off-peak periods
might have no effect

01:04:09.790 --> 01:04:12.310
or could even potentially
actually increase costs.

01:04:12.310 --> 01:04:14.650
AUDIENCE: It could-- well,
yeah, it shouldn't increase.

01:04:14.650 --> 01:04:15.940
It shouldn't increase costs.

01:04:15.940 --> 01:04:18.190
AUDIENCE: Well, I was
going to ask, is there--

01:04:18.190 --> 01:04:20.875
is it ever the case that
off-peak service, when

01:04:20.875 --> 01:04:24.010
there is really low
demand, exists simply

01:04:24.010 --> 01:04:26.440
for the convenience of
scheduling shifts rather

01:04:26.440 --> 01:04:30.867
than meeting maximum headways,
or anything like that?

01:04:30.867 --> 01:04:32.450
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Potentially,

01:04:32.450 --> 01:04:36.020
but because driver costs are
not the only cost of operating

01:04:36.020 --> 01:04:40.670
service, you would then also
agree to spend extra fuel

01:04:40.670 --> 01:04:42.390
and extra maintenance costs.

01:04:42.390 --> 01:04:47.600
And that is also a
significant portion of a cost.

01:04:47.600 --> 01:04:48.920
It's not just free.

01:04:48.920 --> 01:04:51.920
Or it's only-- only
this part may be free,

01:04:51.920 --> 01:04:53.735
not the whole thing.

01:04:53.735 --> 01:04:57.860
But yeah, I think, if you
find yourself in a situation

01:04:57.860 --> 01:05:04.790
where your labor agreement
requires you to have--

01:05:04.790 --> 01:05:07.430
maybe there is a cap on how
much spread you can have.

01:05:07.430 --> 01:05:08.930
So you have all
these straight runs.

01:05:08.930 --> 01:05:11.390
And they're only
working for four hours.

01:05:11.390 --> 01:05:15.500
And then you say, well, you
know, let's add service.

01:05:15.500 --> 01:05:18.530
And let's make the
off-peak service very good.

01:05:18.530 --> 01:05:21.170
So yeah, that could happen,
but it's a management decision.

01:05:21.170 --> 01:05:22.780
That's not something
with the science.

01:05:22.780 --> 01:05:27.060
It's a policy
managerial decision.

01:05:27.060 --> 01:05:28.980
Yeah?

01:05:28.980 --> 01:05:32.076
AUDIENCE: On the last slide
when you were talking about peak

01:05:32.076 --> 01:05:34.940
buses, if we're
decreasing [INAUDIBLE],,

01:05:34.940 --> 01:05:36.450
is it indicative of agency size?

01:05:36.450 --> 01:05:37.700
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Yes.

01:05:37.700 --> 01:05:40.640
So in this example,
we only have three--

01:05:40.640 --> 01:05:42.420
well, we have nine
exploratory variables,

01:05:42.420 --> 01:05:45.500
which are the combination of
the three resource variables

01:05:45.500 --> 01:05:46.710
and the three cost types.

01:05:46.710 --> 01:05:49.970
But if you go back to the
first example in this lecture,

01:05:49.970 --> 01:05:52.250
we had three explanatory
variables-- bus hours,

01:05:52.250 --> 01:05:53.910
bus miles, and peak buses.

01:05:53.910 --> 01:05:56.910
And we have to assign everything
to one of these three.

01:05:56.910 --> 01:06:03.260
So of those three,
peak buses is something

01:06:03.260 --> 01:06:07.820
that most closely relates to how
large your agency is, much more

01:06:07.820 --> 01:06:10.350
so than bus hours or bus miles.

01:06:10.350 --> 01:06:13.100
And if you had other
variables, then

01:06:13.100 --> 01:06:15.980
maybe those would be even
closer to agency size.

01:06:15.980 --> 01:06:18.960
But in this example, we
only have these three--

01:06:18.960 --> 01:06:19.460
yeah.

01:06:22.730 --> 01:06:24.170
And why peak buses?

01:06:24.170 --> 01:06:25.760
Well, because if
you have more buses,

01:06:25.760 --> 01:06:27.510
you need a bigger
parking garage for them.

01:06:27.510 --> 01:06:30.920
You need a bigger refueling
and maintenance facility.

01:06:30.920 --> 01:06:33.050
You might need more
mechanics and more-- right?

01:06:33.050 --> 01:06:36.200
So the many costs
that are mostly

01:06:36.200 --> 01:06:37.970
fixed scale up with
how many vehicles

01:06:37.970 --> 01:06:43.390
you have on your garage,
and how many garages you

01:06:43.390 --> 01:06:46.790
have, and all those things.

01:06:46.790 --> 01:06:49.360
Another detail which
I want to emphasize

01:06:49.360 --> 01:06:52.310
is that, with regards
to the variable

01:06:52.310 --> 01:06:56.380
and fixed, so again, if you
have to incur an expense that

01:06:56.380 --> 01:07:00.350
is more marginal, then you might
want to use a variable cost

01:07:00.350 --> 01:07:06.170
model, because you may not need
another garage, for example,

01:07:06.170 --> 01:07:08.390
