01:11:25.310 --> 01:11:26.960
The reading was
suggesting that you

01:11:26.960 --> 01:11:30.380
could use 15% times the
average, or things like that.

01:11:30.380 --> 01:11:33.230
When you have data, then
you should use the data.

01:11:33.230 --> 01:11:37.760
So the technique of
taking an average

01:11:37.760 --> 01:11:39.290
and multiplying
it by a percentage

01:11:39.290 --> 01:11:42.659
is what the industry
typically does

01:11:42.659 --> 01:11:44.450
when you don't have
automatically collected

01:11:44.450 --> 01:11:47.180
data, when you
essentially send someone

01:11:47.180 --> 01:11:51.200
out to drive behind the bus
or to do-- or a ride checker

01:11:51.200 --> 01:11:53.060
to collect data on the bus.

01:11:53.060 --> 01:11:57.485
And you do five, or
six, maybe 10 trips.

01:11:57.485 --> 01:11:58.790
And then you get an average.

01:11:58.790 --> 01:12:01.675
And that's not enough to
estimate your high percentiles,

01:12:01.675 --> 01:12:03.800
because you probably didn't
see the high percentile

01:12:03.800 --> 01:12:05.300
in those only 10 trips.

01:12:05.300 --> 01:12:09.737
So therefore, you have to
rely on a different method.

01:12:09.737 --> 01:12:11.570
And then you could
multiply by a percentage.

01:12:11.570 --> 01:12:14.840
But if you have data, then
you should use the data.

01:12:14.840 --> 01:12:19.580
And 10%, 15%, 20%,
whatever you use

01:12:19.580 --> 01:12:22.571
might not be adequate
